div2.p:
Another correspondence in style is provided by a token of Cirencester in Gloucestershire,
                  where a phoenix is stylistically very similar to our eagle, especially in the depiction of the wings (Gloucs.44;
                     fig. 13).

I would argue that the mute obverse of our piece indicates it was made at or in the area around Bristol around 1670;
                  this is suggested by the geographical distribution of coins with mute obverses, and is also what we might expect, given the importance of
                     Bristol in the trade with British North America.

list.item:
104. Shilling, Noe 10: "witch piece," 72.3 gr (4.69 g), 11:00 o'clock;
                        D. C. Wismer estate; New Netherlands Coin Company sale Oct. 5, 1951, 19, realized
                     $27.50, purchased by the ANS using monies from the George Hubbard Clapp Fund; ANS 1951.155.3.

107. Shilling, Noe 13, 47.6 gr (3.08 g), 12:00 o'clock; Massachusetts Historical Society; Joseph Lasser collection;
                     contemporary counterfeit. This coin was earlier used for the photograph in Noe's
                     monograph.

127. Shilling, Noe 28, misstruck, 67.0 gr (4.34 g), 12:10 o'clock;
                        Walter Breen; Warfield consignment to mail bid sale held by Alfred Hutter of Baltimore, Nov. 8, 1952, 1370, estimate $75, price realized $49; purchased by the ANS,
                     using monies from the George Hubbard Clapp fund; ANS 1952.180.1.
